RUVASH

David Gerard

2016-06-06

Abstract

I try to get a handle on why variance inflation is a good idea.

Model and Method

First, we generate data where 50% of the genes are null.

library(ruv)
library(ggplot2)

p <- 1000
n <- 10
k <- 5
pi_vals <- c(0.5, 0.3, 0.2)
tau_seq <- c(0, 1, 2)
beta <- succotashr::draw_beta(pi_vals = pi_vals, tau_seq = tau_seq, p = p)
qplot(beta, xlab = "beta", main = "Coefficients", bins = 25)

X <- matrix(c(rep(0, n / 2), rep(1, n / 2)))
X <- (X - mean(X)) / sd(X)

X and Z and independent.

Z <- matrix(rnorm(n * k), nrow = n)

alpha <- matrix(rnorm(k * p), nrow = k)
E <- matrix(rnorm(n * p), nrow = n)
Y <- X %*% beta + Z %*% alpha + E

We’ll let half of the null genes be controls, creating 247 control genes.

which_null <- beta == 0
numnull <- sum(which_null)
ctl <- rep(FALSE, length = p)
ctl[which_null][sample(1:numnull, size = floor(numnull / 2))] <- TRUE

Now we fit RUV4 with inflation

ruvash_out <- ashr::ash_ruv(Y = Y, X = X, ctl = ctl, k = k, posthoc_inflate = FALSE,
                            likelihood = "t")
ruvash_out_normal <- ashr::ash_ruv(Y = Y, X = X, ctl = ctl, k = k, posthoc_inflate = FALSE,
                            gls = FALSE)
ruv4out <- ruv::RUV4(Y = Y, X = X, ctl = ctl, k = k)

XWZ <- cbind(ruv4out$X, ruv4out$W, ruv4out$Z)

mult1 <- solve(t(XWZ) %*% XWZ)[1, 1]
mult2 <- solve(t(X) %*% X)[1, 1]
1 / ruvash_out$ruv$fnorm_x ^ 2
## [1] 0.1111
mult1
## [1] 0.1619
mult2 * ruvash_out$ruv$multiplier
## [1] 0.2178
mult2 * ruvash_out_normal$ruv$multiplier
## [1] 0.8038
qplot(ruvash_out_normal$ruv$pvalues, c(ruv4out$p)) +
    geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1)

sig2final_ruvash <- ruvash_out$ruv$sigma2 * ruvash_out$ruv$multiplier

mean((ruvash_out$ruv$sebetahat / sqrt(ruv4out$sigma2 * ruv4out$multiplier)) ^ 2)
## [1] 1.345
qplot(ruvash_out$ruv$sebetahat,
      sqrt(ruv4out$sigma2 * ruv4out$multiplier)) +
    geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0)

RUVASH says that pi0 is 0.5381 for the normal likelihood or 0.3057 for the t-likelihood. Using ASH on the RUV4 output, we get an estimated pi0 of

Redo but with independence between X and Z

library(ruv)
library(ggplot2)

p <- 1000
n <- 10
k <- 5
pi_vals <- c(0.5, 0.3, 0.2)
tau_seq <- c(0, 1, 2)
beta <- succotashr::draw_beta(pi_vals = pi_vals, tau_seq = tau_seq, p = p)
qplot(beta, xlab = "beta", main = "Coefficients", bins = 25)

X <- matrix(c(rep(0, n / 2), rep(1, n / 2)))
X <- (X - mean(X)) / sd(X)

We’ll let the covariance between X and Z be an AR-1(0.9) correlation matrix.

cor_mat <- 0.9 ^ abs(outer(1:(k + 1), 1:(k + 1), "-"))
## cor_mat <- diag(k + 1)
## cor_mat[1, 2:ncol(cor_mat)] <- -0.7
## cor_mat[2:ncol(cor_mat), 1] <- -0.7
## cor_mat[2:ncol(cor_mat), 2:ncol(cor_mat)] <- 0.5
## diag(cor_mat) <- 1

cond_cov <- cor_mat[2:ncol(cor_mat), 2:ncol(cor_mat)] -
    t(cor_mat[1, 2:ncol(cor_mat), drop = FALSE]) %*%
    cor_mat[1, 2:ncol(cor_mat), drop = FALSE] / cor_mat[1, 1]
cond_mean <- X %*% cor_mat[1, 2:ncol(cor_mat), drop = FALSE] / cor_mat[1, 1]

half_cov <- chol(cond_cov)

Z <- cond_mean + matrix(rnorm(n * k), nrow = n) %*% half_cov

alpha <- matrix(rnorm(k * p), nrow = k)
E <- matrix(rnorm(n * p), nrow = n)
Y <- X %*% beta + Z %*% alpha + E

We’ll let half of the null genes be controls, creating 251 control genes.

which_null <- beta == 0
numnull <- sum(which_null)
ctl <- rep(FALSE, length = p)
ctl[which_null][sample(1:numnull, size = floor(numnull / 2))] <- TRUE

Now we fit RUV4 with inflation

ruvash_out <- ashr::ash_ruv(Y = Y, X = X, ctl = ctl, k = k, posthoc_inflate = FALSE,
                            likelihood = "t")
ruvash_out_normal <- ashr::ash_ruv(Y = Y, X = X, ctl = ctl, k = k, posthoc_inflate = FALSE,
                            gls = FALSE)

XWZ <- cbind(ruv4out$X, ruv4out$W, ruv4out$Z)

mult1 <- solve(t(XWZ) %*% XWZ)[1, 1]
mult2 <- solve(t(X) %*% X)[1, 1]
1 / ruvash_out$ruv$fnorm_x ^ 2
## [1] 0.1111
mult1
## [1] 0.5758
mult2 * ruvash_out$ruv$multiplier
## [1] 0.658
mult2 * ruvash_out_normal$ruv$multiplier
## [1] 1.706
qplot(ruvash_out_normal$ruv$pvalues, c(ruv4out$p)) +
    geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1)

sig2final_ruvash <- ruvash_out$ruv$sigma2 * ruvash_out$ruv$multiplier

mean((ruvash_out$ruv$sebetahat / sqrt(ruv4out$sigma2 * ruv4out$multiplier)) ^ 2)
## [1] 1.143
qplot(ruvash_out$ruv$sebetahat,
      sqrt(ruv4out$sigma2 * ruv4out$multiplier)) +
    geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0)

RUVASH says that pi0 is 0.4432 for the normal likelihood or 0.2756 for the t-likelihood. Using ASH on the RUV4 output, we get an estimated pi0 of

lfdr ordering changes in ASH if scale standard deviations.

ash_out <- ashr::ash(betahat = ruv4out$betahat,
                     sebetahat = sqrt(ruv4out$sigma2 * ruv4out$multiplier))
ash_out2 <- ashr::ash(betahat = ruv4out$betahat,
                     sebetahat = sqrt(ruv4out$sigma2 * ruv4out$multiplier * 1.5))
qplot(ash_out$lfdr, ash_out2$lfdr)

ash_out$fitted.g$pi[1]
## [1] 0.1987
ash_out2$fitted.g$pi[1]
## [1] 0.2543

GTEX data

RUVASH says that we should have approximately twice the variance that RUV4 says we should have. But this corresponds to a multiplication by 3.368 for the sig_diag_scaled that we calculate.

rm(list = ls())
data_path <- "../../../../Code/rcc_copy/projects/ruvash_gtex_gender/output/cleaned_gtex_data/muscle.Rd"
load(data_path)

ruvash_out <- ashr::ash_ruv(Y = t(muscle$Y), X = muscle$X, ctl = muscle$ctl, k = 32,
                            posthoc_inflate = FALSE, gls = FALSE)
ruv4out <- ruv::RUV4(Y = t(muscle$Y), X = muscle$X[, "Gender", drop = FALSE],
                     ctl = muscle$ctl, k = 32, Z = muscle$X[, -2, drop = FALSE])
XWZ <- cbind(ruv4out$X, ruv4out$W, ruv4out$Z)

mult1 <- solve(t(XWZ) %*% XWZ)[1, 1]
mult2 <- solve(t(muscle$X) %*% muscle$X)[2, 2]

mult1 / mult2
## [1] 1.402
ruvash_out$ruv$multiplier
## [1] 3.368
qplot(ruvash_out$ruv$sigma2, ruv4out$sigma2) +
    geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0)

mult1
## [1] 0.0141
ruv4out$multiplier
##          [,1]
## Gender 0.0141
## should be monotone
qplot(x = c(ruvash_out$ruv$pvalues), y = c(ruv4out$p)) +
    geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0)
